Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday! Welcome to our 7th Weekly Dose of Optimism, where we celebrat=
e the incredible accomplishments humans manage to pull off and the progress=
 that we=E2=80=99re making. We=E2=80=99re never perfect, but I think we=E2=
=80=99re moving in the right direction.=20
If you=E2=80=99re enjoying this Weekly Dose, spread the optimism by forward=
ing this email or sharing the newsletter wherever you share good things.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by my daily dose=E2=80=A6 Athletic Greens=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/4dfafb5d-6a0f-4878-be94-0337af64e672?r=3D9=
p0gt ]
Every morning, I drink a homemade concoction starring Athletic Greens=E2=80=
=99 AG1 [ https://substack.com/redirect/d4fcd39f-7f43-425f-9283-c3a7a337b7d=
e?r=3D9p0gt ]. It=E2=80=99s one of the few products I actually use daily.
An AG1 subscription isn=E2=80=99t cheap =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s ~$79/month o=
r almost $1,000 year. But if being at the top of your game is as important =
to you as it is to me, it=E2=80=99s worth it.
Get a free one-year supply of Vitamin D and 5 travel packs when you order w=
ith the special Not Boring link [ https://substack.com/redirect/d4fcd39f-7f=
43-425f-9283-c3a7a337b7de?r=3D9p0gt ].
(1) Moderna's Bets: Moonshots and Platforms [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/331d328b-92f3-4c30-a366-b4f371ee1d7b?r=3D9p0gt ]
Byrne Hobart [ https://substack.com/redirect/f29e5a0e-651d-42a3-a9f3-cbad8f=
0c4227?r=3D9p0gt ] for The Diff
The fun way to look at Moderna in 2022 is that it's a wildly exaggerated ve=
rsion of Moderna circa 2019: lots of promising products in the pipeline, lo=
ts of cash with which to pursue them, and a credible claim that each new dr=
ug they launch makes the next ones faster and cheaper to develop.
Byrne is every newsletter writer=E2=80=99s favorite newsletter writer. This=
 week he breaks down one of the most important companies of the last few ye=
ars, Moderna, and explains how its =E2=80=9Cbreakthrough=E2=80=9D on the Co=
vid vaccine wasn=E2=80=99t just a one-off blockbuster success, but rather a=
n instructive case-study on the company=E2=80=99s overall strategy. Here=E2=
=80=99s the upshot: mRNA vaccine & therapeutic early-stage development (as =
pioneered by Moderna) can be orders of magnitude quicker and cheaper than t=
raditional methodologies. This allows Moderna to pursue many different rese=
arch avenues at once, and once they identify a winner, out-scale more focus=
ed, specific developers during the costly periods of late-stage drug develo=
pment.
(2) The Reddit Group Helping to Fund Herpes=C2=A0Vaccine Research [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/d517a0c5-e951-4202-b70d-c36c36b31d20?r=3D9p0gt ]
Mark Hay [ https://substack.com/redirect/37a7120a-929a-462b-9361-ad6091ab22=
df?r=3D9p0gt ] for Inside Hook
To date, the group has raised over $350,000 to support Friedman=E2=80=99s v=
accine research. This sum is nowhere near the cash infusion of a big grant,=
 or industry backing, he acknowledges. But it has allowed him to fill gaps,=
 investing in resources his existing budget would cover, which will help hi=
m speed up and strengthen his work =E2=80=94 like hiring two new full-time =
staff to work on the study.
Not every vaccine research project has the resources of Moderna=E2=80=99s $=
8B balance sheet behind it. When Harvey Friedman=E2=80=99s [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/dfd06c31-b624-478e-b4c4-71694c75a87a?r=3D9p0gt ], a leading=
 herpes researcher, traditional funding for his promising genital herpes va=
ccine came up short, he got support from an unlikely source: r/HerpesCureRe=
search [ https://substack.com/redirect/3aa5a196-679f-4ceb-a2cb-239ba7002ffb=
?r=3D9p0gt ]. Friedman=E2=80=99s vaccine showed promising results during an=
imal testing, but was not getting the necessary funding it needed to enter =
into early stage human trials. The Reddit community stepped up and crowdsou=
rced $350,000 to fill in the funding gaps. A similar concept is being scale=
d by Not Boring Capital portfolio company, Vibe Bio [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/3b4a288e-4562-4472-80c2-f5e4a86fee3e?r=3D9p0gt ], which is a commu=
nity of patients, scientists, and partners committed to funding and treatin=
g rare diseases. Genital herpes is by no means rare =E2=80=94 the CDC estim=
ates 12% of the US population between 14 and 49 have the condition [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/0768cb7b-5fa9-485d-b51a-c531749a2586?r=3D9p0gt ] =
=E2=80=94 but funding for the cure does suffer from the same lack of pharma=
 business model alignment that rare diseases do.
(3) =F0=9F=8E=A7 Carbon Removal Might Be the  Most Important Technology. Ho=
w Does It Work? [ https://substack.com/redirect/125fd22a-0543-47a4-8b90-130=
c7220d031?r=3D9p0gt ] =F0=9F=8E=A7
Derek Thompson [ https://substack.com/redirect/6818ca31-e222-43c5-b668-383c=
76d3b748?r=3D9p0gt ] for The Ringer
I=E2=80=99ve become very interested in a technology called carbon removal=
=E2=80=94and especially direct air capture. Imagine, basically, a giant fac=
tory that pulls carbon from the atmosphere and buries it. This technology i=
s still incredibly expensive. In August 2022, it is not remotely close to b=
eing a global solution to climate change. But there is a chance it may be t=
he most important technology of the 2020s and 2030s.
In January, Derek Thompson, of =E2=80=9CPlain English=E2=80=9D & The Atlant=
ic, proposed the Abundance Agenda [ https://substack.com/redirect/543c5ec9-=
7299-4053-a1c9-79ee00317eea?r=3D9p0gt ] =E2=80=94 the view that the US need=
s to increase its supply of national essentials: houses, physicians, medica=
l tests, immigrants, solar panels, et al. At its core, this policy is meant=
 to make America less vulnerable to things like pandemics, labor shortages,=
 and climate change. The Abundance Agenda advocates for more (and cleaner) =
sources of energy, but if is embraced full-throttle, it likely means the US=
 will become a larger emitter of carbon dioxide. In this episode of Plain E=
nglish, Giana Amador [ https://substack.com/redirect/e8b5157d-26c6-4e30-87b=
8-2cae6f7518a9?r=3D9p0gt ], joins Derek to discuss one path to reducing our=
 carbon footprint while still pursuing the Abundance Agenda =E2=80=94 carbo=
n capture.
(4) Serena Williams Says Farewell to Tennis On Her Own Terms=E2=80=94And In=
 Her Own Words [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e2cec2b-3e09-40ff-ba9e-8c2d=
6e4235e8?r=3D9p0gt ]
Serena Williams [ https://substack.com/redirect/3a83729d-129e-48c9-905d-e49=
d2d32fba7?r=3D9p0gt ] for Vogue
I=E2=80=99ve built a career on channeling anger and negativity and turning =
it into something good. My sister Venus once said that when someone out the=
re says you can=E2=80=99t do something, it is because they can=E2=80=99t do=
 it. But I did do it. And so can you.
Not Boring isn=E2=80=99t a sports blog. Neither is Vogue. But we both recog=
nize greatness. It=E2=80=99s pretty incredible to see humans perform at the=
 absolute peak. And for the last 20+ years, Serena Williams has been at the=
 top of the tennis world: 23 Grand Slam singles titles, an 85% win rate, an=
d 319 weeks ranked #1 in the world. Tennis has been basically her whole lif=
e for as long as she remembers, but she makes it clear: she is not happy ab=
out =E2=80=9Cretiring.=E2=80=9D She doesn=E2=80=99t want to do it. It=E2=80=
=99s amazing how manically focused ultra-high performers are =E2=80=94 even=
 after ~35 years of all-encompassing tennis, Serena needs to be dragged off=
 the court.=20
While we typically talk about technological progress in the Weekly Dose, it=
=E2=80=99s pretty incredible how far human performance has progressed in ju=
st the last century. For video proof, check out this tweet showing how gymn=
astics changed between 1912 and 2012.=20
(5) Has Technological Progress Stalled? [ https://substack.com/redirect/74b=
4fff7-28ae-40d2-9777-109037017780?r=3D9p0gt ]
Tanner Greer [ https://substack.com/redirect/25aa7cdd-1dac-4051-b68d-bb8a31=
5d4329?r=3D9p0gt ] for The Scholar=E2=80=99s Stage. Submitted by @archimbol=
dii [ https://substack.com/redirect/8cd91e61-7f98-406e-92bf-26cfeb97fcb6?r=
=3D9p0gt ]
A future boom will not come from improvements in organization and informati=
on. It will be from inventing new materials to build from, new ways to move=
 what we build, or new sources of energy to power our building. This is my =
yardstick for evaluating the =E2=80=9Crevolutionary=E2=80=9D potential of n=
ew technologies.
Essayist Tanner Greer responds to Mary Harrington=E2=80=99s [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/1086fbac-0243-4bbb-8714-4c7bc5b8908f?r=3D9p0gt ] long-form=
 interview of Peter Thiel [ https://substack.com/redirect/a8eacf3f-f6b9-42c=
8-9d1d-b03e12e7e804?r=3D9p0gt ], in which Thiel explains his belief that te=
chnological progress stopped in the early 1970=E2=80=99s. Greer, aligning m=
ore closely with Professor Vaclav Smil [ https://substack.com/redirect/0820=
f7fd-c328-4dc3-a6ac-80545facbc86?r=3D9p0gt ] than Thiel, argues that the US=
 has been experiencing stagnation since the pre-Word War I period. True per=
iods of technological progress don=E2=80=99t come from improvements in orga=
nization or information transmission, Greer asserts, but rather from physic=
al transformation of the world around us. =E2=80=9CIt means mud to concrete=
=2E Wood to steel. Sweat to dynamos. Shov=
els to dynamite. Wicks to lightbulbs=
=2E Carts to cars to aeroplanes.=E2=80=9D=
 On one hand, Greer=E2=80=99s view o=
f progress is pessimistic =E2=80=94 claiming that we have not achieved many=
 foundational breakthroughs in the last ~100+ years. On the other, it=E2=80=
=99s optimistic: quality of life has undoubtedly improved in the last 100+ =
years [ https://substack.com/redirect/0acae758-00a8-45f5-b864-d3911a511246?=
r=3D9p0gt ], and that improvement has come without any major periods of pro=
gress (in Greer=E2=80=99s view.)
There=E2=80=99s something appealing about the view that Greer borrows from =
Smil =E2=80=94 essentially, that progress should be measured in joules =E2=
=80=94 and while I=E2=80=99m not sure I agree with the whole essay, I=E2=80=
=99m in strong favor of a world with more, cheaper joules.=20
